<DOC><DOCNO> AP891207-0149 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-07-89 1854EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-07 0325</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0337</SECOND><HEAD>Winter Storm Covers Plains</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The Plains got a blast of winter Thursday as a storm left morethan a foot of snow in places, while a second winter storm warningwas posted for the mid-Atlantic states.   Snowfall was heaviest in the West. Colorado snow cover included17 inches at Rye, with 8 inches at Beulah, West Cliff andWalsenburg. Story, Wyo., had 11 inches of snow and 5 inches fell atSheridan, Wyo.   Roads over the Texas Panhandle were ice-covered Thursdaymorning. At least three inches of snow fell on Amarillo, Texas, andup to two inches of snow accumulated in parts of Nebraska.   Mild temperatures melted much of the snow and turned it intofreezing rain. ``It's melting about as fast as it's falling,'' saidBill Wyatt, a spokesman for the city of Woodward, Okla., whichreceived about 3 inches of snow.   During the day snow fell over the southwestern third of NorthDakota, much of South Dakota, north-central through westernNebraska, northeast Colorado, much of Kansas into southwestMissouri, northern and western Oklahoma, the Texas Panhandle andnorthwest Texas.   In the East, a winter storm warning was posted for Friday overthe southern and western half of Virginia, northeast Tennessee,southeast Kentucky and much of western North Carolina.   Snow showers fell Thursday across central and western New Yorkstate, northwest Pennsylvania and northeast Ohio. Snow extendedover upper Michigan and western lower Michigan.   Rain reached across Arkansas, eastern Louisiana, Mississippi,Alabama, northern Georgia and South Carolina.   Heavier rainfall during the 6 hours ending at 1 p.m. ESTincluded an inch at Jackson, Miss., .72 of an inch at Lafayette,La., and .70 of an inch at McComb, Miss.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EST ranged from zerodegrees at Warroad, Minn., to 85 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.Thelow temperature for the nation Thursday morning was 15 degreesbelow zero at Warroad, Minn.</TEXT></DOC>